Course Overview:
This workshop will provide attendees with the opportunity to learn how (1)
to understand; (2) run simulations of readily available Individual Based
Models (IBMs); (3) analyze the outputs of IBMs; (4) parameterize IBMs, and
(5) code relatively basic IBMs in R and NetLogo.
Examples and applications will include cases from diverse domains and
scientific disciplines such as social sciences, biology, and environmental
sciences.

Intended Audience:
This workshop is ideal for any scientists seeking an introduction as well
as functional use in terms of parameterizing, simulating, and analyzing
outputs of IBMs; some moderate skills of programming and own coding will
also be acquired.
This course will suite attendees from a diverse range of scientific
disciplines such as biology, ecology, psychology, economics, or education.
No prior knowledge of programming in R or Netlogo are required. However
basic to moderate prior R knowledge is required (loading data, loading R
packages, basic R environment and basic R commands).

